Summary and Explanation of the Described Semiconductor Device 

Description of a MEMS (Micro-Electro-Mechanical System) structure. 

This refers to German Patent DE 4332653 C1 (published in 1995). 

patents.google.com

Core of the Invention
A monolithically integrated semiconductor element is described, in which the following structures are 
fabricated in a single piece from a single silicon wafer: A thin membrane (diaphragm)
- A beam structure (beam/web) arranged above it
- The beams rest on support beams (support beams/anchors)

Distinctive Feature 
All elements (diaphragm + support beams + beams) are monolithically (without gluing, bonding, or separate assembly) 
fabricated from a single monocrystalline silicon substrate. The edges and surfaces are formed by anisotropic 
etching, which exhibits significantly different etching rates depending on the crystal orientation.

Fabrication Process (brief)
Masking on both sides of a silicon substrate with a defined crystal orientation.
Altering the crystal structure (e.g., through implantation or other methods to selectively influence the etch rate).
Anisotropic wet etching (typically with KOH or TMAH). Etching continues until the support beams are exposed.

A defined thin membrane remains beneath the webs.

Particularly suitable: monocrystalline silicon with <110> surface orientation. This orientation allows for specific 
geometric shapes (vertical walls or special angles) that are not as easily achievable with <100> wafers. 

