Advantages of this design
Very good mechanical coupling between the beams and the membrane (no adhesive joints or bonded connections → higher 
reliability and reproducibility).
Precisely defined geometries due to crystallographically determined etching stops ({111} planes etch extremely slowly).
Suitable as a sensor (e.g., pressure sensor, accelerometer, resonator) or electromechanical transducer (actuator).

Typical applications of such structures: piezoresistive or capacitive sensors
- Microphones
- Resonance sensors (mass or force sensors)
- AFM cantilever-like structures on a membrane

Technical Background
In the anisotropic etching of silicon (e.g., with KOH), the following applies:
{111} planes are hardly etched at all → natural etch stops.
<110> wafers enable vertical or steep sidewalls and complex cantilevered structures.

The additional “planar destruction or partial destruction of the crystal structure” (e.g., through ion implantation) 
likely serves to locally control the etch rate in order to precisely achieve the desired membrane thickness and the 
exposure of the beams.
